43:50.752 --> 43:51.332
Three words?

43:51.352 --> 43:53.715
Yes.

43:53.915 --> 44:07.875
But the thing is that by the time the big Coast Guard boat came, which is offshore, then four men came up in a zodiac or something.

44:10.118 --> 44:16.868
They tried to walk me down, but I was too weak, my legs were too weak to get over that slippery rock wave.

44:17.509 --> 44:21.795
So they laid me on a stretcher and bound me across the shoulders.

44:22.501 --> 44:31.873
It was the most helpless feeling I've ever had, just looking up at this gray mess, it was getting sort of dark, and I saw Alicia's storm petrel fly over.

44:32.474 --> 44:35.197
It was an appropriate bird to see, but I don't know whether I really saw it.

44:36.178 --> 44:42.787
And by midnight I was in the hospital at Boothbay to check my vital signs.

44:42.807 --> 44:51.057
I was there two days, and my heart was okay, even though I'd been struggling so much that my heart hurt.

44:51.728 --> 44:54.291
And my hip was not broken as I thought it was.

44:55.232 --> 44:58.015
I was in better shape when I went out of the hospital than when I got in.

44:58.095 --> 45:13.173
But the hospital had the rule that not to talk to reporters about any person in trouble, because maybe the person who was in trouble didn't want to know what was wrong.

45:13.193 --> 45:21.583
In fact, I would have been happy to have people know that the nurse never

45:22.120 --> 45:27.208
So the New York Times tried to piece it together about their own, and they came close to being correct.

45:27.228 --> 45:29.792
They were being correct.

45:29.812 --> 45:30.994
They were the closest to anybody.

45:33.758 --> 45:40.949
But in one news report it was an eighteen-foot boat, and another report it was a forty-two-foot boat, and another was a thirty-fourth.

45:41.630 --> 45:44.835
See, they were all getting— Sure.

45:44.855 --> 45:45.236
Well, what was it?

45:45.256 --> 45:46.037
How many feet?

45:46.057 --> 45:49.242
It was about thirty-two.

45:51.938 --> 45:55.502
Well, what wisdom do you glean from this experience?

45:55.843 --> 45:58.486
Never to go out without a life jacket on.

45:58.606 --> 46:03.832
Well, that's fundamental, but I wonder if there's anything, any wisdom.

46:04.293 --> 46:06.596
Every day is important in your life.

46:07.076 --> 46:21.574
And if I had just gotten one really bad review by Kenny Parks again, I don't remember his name, I would have taken another couple of gulps.

46:22.162 --> 46:27.731
No, mainly it's because I had two books to finish.

46:27.751 --> 46:29.894
He had books to do.

46:29.914 --> 46:31.277
He had to go on.

46:31.357 --> 46:32.879
I couldn't give it.

46:33.080 --> 46:36.505
Is there a secret to this, Mr. Peterson?

46:36.545 --> 46:39.810
Can you explain what it is?

46:39.850 --> 46:42.635
No, why I should be so lucky.

46:43.176 --> 46:44.558
Any one of those five people.

46:44.639 --> 46:46.181
I'm not just talking about that incident.

46:46.221 --> 46:51.606
I'm just talking about the inspirational example you give to all of us.

46:51.626 --> 46:52.988
I mean, eighty-six years old.

46:53.949 --> 46:54.850
Well, I have more to do.

46:54.870 --> 47:00.456
I think it's as simple as that.

47:00.476 --> 47:04.040
Well, that's a good one to end on, isn't it?

47:04.060 --> 47:14.511
I don't want to overstate my... Well, the main thing, I'm going to be careful in the Antarctic, because I've had one or two close calls down there in

47:14.913 --> 47:20.538
Because of waves and boat trouble.

47:20.558 --> 47:22.040
No, you're not going on this trip.

47:22.060 --> 47:29.827
No, I've been five times, and last Christmas I was there for about almost a month.

47:29.847 --> 47:35.713
And my children asked if I could please have Christmas with them this year.

47:36.494 --> 47:38.516
So I asked Roger, sorry if I stayed home this year.

47:38.536 --> 47:39.497
I'm not sure.

47:39.517 --> 47:41.899
I've got this wonderful man going once on the floor.

47:42.065 --> 47:44.208
We'll take good care of them.

47:44.228 --> 47:45.650
Russ Kenny.

47:45.670 --> 47:48.654
She's worked out very well.

47:48.854 --> 47:51.157
I love the Antarctic, too.

47:51.618 --> 47:53.220
It never gets boring, does it, to you?

47:53.240 --> 47:53.781
It never does.

47:56.965 --> 48:03.174
I could say I don't really have to do this, but I want to improve on things I've done in the past.

48:03.815 --> 48:07.780
In the Falklands, you've always wanted to spend more time in the Falklands.

48:07.800 --> 48:10.063
I presume I'll not have another Antarctic trip.

48:10.564 --> 48:11.565
I just want to do it right.

48:11.782 --> 48:24.233
See, I've gotten some awfully good pictures in the Antarctic, but there are certain things that have to do with depth perception and that that I can improve on.

48:24.994 --> 48:26.815
Lerch is known as the king penguin, too.

48:26.835 --> 48:28.817
That might be interesting for your audience.

48:28.837 --> 48:32.420
Well, my friends in Texas call me the king penguins.

48:33.381 --> 48:37.525
I don't really have a—I'm not quite sure what my favorite bird is.

48:37.545 --> 48:41.248
I could say it's the Flicker, because that's the bird that hooked me.

48:41.633 --> 48:45.138
I could say it's the Blue Jay because it was the first bird I drew.

48:45.158 --> 48:48.022
I could say it's the Oscar.

48:49.143 --> 48:52.328
I repeat myself.

48:52.708 --> 48:54.771
That's okay.

48:55.592 --> 49:01.280
When people ask me, what is my favorite bird, I find it difficult to answer because I like all birds.

49:01.821 --> 49:09.632
But in my boyhood, it was the Piliated woodpecker, the big flamboyant woodpecker.

49:09.848 --> 49:17.418
I could say that the blue jay is my favorite bird because that was the first bird I learned to draw, the first bird I tried to draw, rather.

49:17.458 --> 49:31.918
And I could say the flicker is my favorite bird, and it probably really should be because it was the bird that hooked me on watching birds.

49:31.938 --> 49:37.746
I've told this story several times about this bundle of brown feathers on the tree trunk and I just

49:38.249 --> 49:42.194
I thought it was dead and it was very much alive when I poked it.

49:43.076 --> 49:51.507
And this contrast between death and life, or what I thought was dead and what was alive, was like resurrection.

49:51.547 --> 50:07.429
And I could say in a way that the Osprey is a favorite bird, which is the one that I've been most concerned with, helping it make its comeback here in the East.

50:08.793 --> 50:19.627
And as a family of birds, the penguins are my favorite family, and I enjoy the king penguin most because it's so colorful and flamboyant.

50:20.628 --> 50:24.212
And my friends in Texas call me the king penguin.

50:25.234 --> 50:30.200
This group in Texas always gives bird names to various people.

50:30.620 --> 50:31.501
They choose the name.

50:31.682 --> 50:34.305
You don't have anything to do with that.

50:34.325 --> 50:38.310
Ginny's called the Woodthrust because she sings well.

50:38.678 --> 50:39.800
has to keep out of the sun.

50:42.444 --> 50:43.706
So she's called the Woodthrust.

50:44.066 --> 50:45.007
That's great.

50:46.049 --> 50:48.212
At any rate, I'm the King Penguin.

50:48.232 --> 50:52.298
I don't know why I'm not the Emperor Penguin.

50:52.399 --> 50:59.249
I know you've got another interview coming up, so I think I'm going to give you a few minutes to get ready for your next interview.

50:59.329 --> 51:01.412
You've been very generous with your time.

